## âڈ³ Trust Decay Protocol

When reviewing code in a living codebase, assess not just the current state but
how surrounding changes may have eroded previously-safe assumptions.

### Decay Factors

For each function analyzed, scan for decay signals since its last review:

| Factor | Signal | Decay Effect |
|--------|--------|:--:|
| **Caller growth** | New callers; existing callers grew in complexity | Trust أ—0.85 |
| **Dependency change** | Callee had HIGH-severity vulnerability fix | Trust أ—0.70 |
| **Proximity churn** | >3 adjacent files modified | Trust أ—0.90 |
| **Time decay** | Long time since last review | Trust أ—0.95/month |
| **Commit density** ًں”´ | >10 commits in one day on same file â†’ rush risk | Trust أ—0.75 |
| **Off-hours commits** ًںŒ™ | Midnight-6am commits â†’ 2أ— bug density in studies | Trust أ—0.80 |
| **Code age U-curve** | Very new (<1mo) OR very old (>2yr) â†’ higher risk | Trust أ—0.85 at extremes |
| **Hot-path drift** | Function was hot path 6mo ago but no recent profiling | Trust أ—0.90 â€” may be optimizing dead code |

### Report Format

```
âڈ³ TRUST DECAY ASSESSMENT:
   [If no decay signals found â€” function's context is stable. Trust: HIGH.]

   [If decay signals found:]
   Function [X]: original Health Score [Y], last reviewed [time] ago.
   Decay: [factor1] أ—[decay] + [factor2] أ—[decay] = effective trust [new score].
   Recommendation: [Re-review / Monitor / No action].
```

**Rule:** Apply to the primary function being analyzed. If no git history is available,
state "No version history available â€” trust decay cannot be assessed."

Theoretical foundation: ًںŒ،ï¸ڈ Software Thermodynamics â€” entropy only increases in unmaintained code.

### Zero-Day Susceptibility Score
For each dependency: ZDS = (depth أ— exposure أ— privilege) / isolation.
Depth: how deep in the call chain. Exposure: network-facing? Privilege: runs as root/admin?
Isolation: sandboxed/containerized? ZDS > 70: ًں”´ If this dep has a zero-day, full compromise is likely.

